# Architecture Diagrams

## C4 Model

Use the C4 model for progressive architecture visualization:

| Level | Name | Shows | Audience |
|-------|------|-------|----------|
| 1 | Context | System + external actors | Everyone |
| 2 | Container | Applications, databases, message brokers | Technical leads |
| 3 | Component | Major components within a container | Developers |
| 4 | Code | Class-level detail | Do NOT generate (use IDE) |

### Rules
- Always start with Level 1 (Context) before diving deeper
- Never generate Level 4 diagrams -- use IDE class diagrams instead
- Each container should map to a deployable unit
- Label all relationships with protocol and purpose

## Diagram Types

| Type | Use For | Tool |
|------|---------|------|
| C4 Context/Container/Component | System architecture | PlantUML + C4-PlantUML |
| Sequence diagram | API flows, service interactions | PlantUML |
| Class diagram | Domain model, type hierarchies | PlantUML |
| ER diagram | Database schema | PlantUML (Chen notation) |
| State machine | Entity lifecycle, workflow states | PlantUML |

## PlantUML Conventions

- Store diagrams as `.puml` files in `docs/diagrams/`
- Use `!include` for shared styles and C4 macros
- Add `title`, `footer`, and version info to every diagram
- Keep diagrams focused: one concern per diagram file

## Naming

- `c4-context.puml`, `c4-container-api.puml`
- `seq-order-creation.puml`, `class-domain-model.puml`
- `er-schema.puml`, `state-order-lifecycle.puml`

